title: Birds of the Macedon Ranges
description: Birds spotted in the Macedon Range (not the shire area).

items.content_text: Very excited to spot Erythrogonoys cinctus with my new binoculars. First time spot.

items.title: Petroica boodang
items.content_text:
Giving a bit of colour to winter in the Macedon Ranges. 
I'm not sure what the small olive birds are that these robins tend to hang around with. They are too fast for me to get a photo of.

items.title: Cracticus tibicen
items.content_text: The only bird tame enough for me to get a nice photo of. We have a family of 5 which tap on the kitchen window of a morning.

items.title: Malurus cyaneus
items.content_text: The Malurus cyaneus are so bright at this time of year.

items.title: Zosterops lateralis

items.title: Phylidonyris novaehollandiae
items.content_text: A striking little honeyeater, posing for the camera just near Bolobek Lake.

items.title: Alisterus scapularis
items.content_text: A pair of well fed and confident King Parrots

items.title: Coracina novaehollandiae
items.content_text: A family group of black-faced cuckoo-shrikes flying from tree to tree. Juveniles calling loudly and begging for food.

items.title: Sericornis frontalis
items.content_text: Juvenile or female. The bird was so tame/inquisitive I could use my close-up lens! Note the pale grey eye colour of this individual. The eyes are more often pale yellow, I think.

items.title: Callocephalon fimbriatum
items.content_text: One of a noisy flock of 10 Gang-gang Cockatoos feeding on grubs in an Acacia mearnsii. They all looked to be young males with developing red head-feathering. They were quite unfazed by my close presence.

items.title: Threskiornis molucca
items.content_text: Occasionally a fearless lone white ibis wanders around our backyard.

items.title: Dacelo novaeguineae
items.content_text: Sitting on the window-sill watching its reflection. It let me get VERY close and stayed there for around 5 minutes then flew off. Very beautiful.

items.title: Lichenostomus chrysops
items.content_text:
Feeding on cultivated Eucalyptus crenulata.
Blue eyes.

items.title: Melithreptus lunatus
items.content_text: Comparison of adult and immature White-naped Honeyeater. The immature bird has a brown head and the eye crescent and base of bill are both orange.

items.title: Oriolus sagittatus
items.content_text:
We have been seeing this bird feeding on the small grapes on the vine on our verandah.
It takes fright easily but the shape, size and  black-streaks on the white belly give a positive identification.
It flies off quickly with the slightest disturbance before a photo can be taken.

items.title: Daphoenositta chrysoptera pileata
items.content_text: Male. 2nd pic shows typical upside-down foraging position while searching for insects. Group of about a dozen birds. This seems to be one of the most eastern records for Race pileata. See female in 9022.

items.title: Daphoenositta chrysoptera pileata
items.content_text: Female. Group of about a dozen birds. This seems to be one of the most eastern records for Race pileata. See also 9023.

items.title: Turnix varius
items.content_text: 3rd pic shows stationary, crouched position when caught in the open with Kookaburras calling as they flew over. Stayed motionless for about a minute.

items.title: Alisterus scapularis
items.content_text: Female King Parrot. These birds are rarely seen at Mt Macedon.

items.title: Rhipidura rufifrons
items.content_text: Doing a beautiful skipping dance in the undergrowth.

items.title: Chalcites lucidus
items.content_text: Flew into window. Placed in bush to recover by Barry Best.

items.title: Podargus strigoides
items.content_text: Pair spotted roosting on a dead Blackwood, among Eucalyptus aromaphloia. Second pic shows wing-marks on our window - the birds are feasting on Rain Moths (Hepialidae) on the windows at night at this time of year.
